definition.value: A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid that is glutamic acid substituted by a hydroxy and a methyl group at position 4.
A 4-hydroxy-4-methylglutamic acid that has L-configuration.
A nona-2,4,6-trienal in which the double bonds at positions 2 and 4 adopt trans-configuration and the double bond at position 6 adopts cis-configuration.
A fatty acid methyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 8(9)-EET with methanol.
A fatty acid methyl ester that is sebacic acid  in which both carboxy groups are replaced by methoxycarbonyl groups.
A fatty acid methyl ester that is nonanedioic acid in which both carboxy groups are replaced by methoxycarbonyl groups.
A primary aliphatic amine that is 3-aminopropan-1-ol in which the hydroxy group is replaced by a (2-ethylhexyl)oxy group.
An N-acylpiperidine that is piperidin-4-amine substituted at position 1 by a furan-2-ylcarbonyl group.
An aminopiperidine that is piperidin-3-amine substituted by a [(prop-2-en-1-yl)oxy]carbonyl group at position 1.
A pyrrolidin-2-one substituted by 6-carboxyhexyl and 3-hydroxyoctyl groups at positions 1 and 2, respectively. It is a potent prostaglandin EP4 receptor agonist (Ki=35 nM).

A member of the class of indoles that is 1H-indole which is substituted at position 1 by a pentyl group and at position 3 by a (4-methoxyphenyl)acetyl group. It is a synthetic cannabinoid with relatively poor affinity for both CB1 (Ki = 1064 nM) and CB2 (Ki = 444 nM) receptors.

An oligopeptide comprising of L-threonine, L-proline, L-proline, L-alanine, glycine, L-proline, L-aspartic acid, L-valine, glycine, L-proline, and L-arginine amino acids joined in sequence by peptide linkages. It is isolated from the venoms of three species of New World pit vipers from the subfamily, Crotalinae.

An isoquinolinol that is 1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinoline substituted by a methyl group at position 1 and by hydroxy groups at positions 6 and 7.
The organic cationic group formed from L-leucinium; the major structure at pH 7.3 of the L-leucyl group, formed by protonation of the alpha-amino group.
An N-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue derived from N-acetyl-L-leucine.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 3-[({5-[(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)methyl]-4-ethyl-4H-1,2,4-triazol-3-yl}sulfanyl)methyl]benzoic acid with the amino group of 2,3-dimethylaniline.

A fatty acid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of isovaleric acid with the hydroxy group of hex-3-en-1-ol.
A 3-hexenyl isovalerate in which the double bond adopts trans-configuration.

A synthetic beta-D-glucoside that is a branched pentasaccharide derivative consisting of two glucose residues, two rhamnose residues (out of which one is acetylated at the 2nd position) and one N-acetylglucosamine residue with at the reducing end an aminoethyl linker allowing for efficient conjugation to a carrier protein. The basic structure (i.e. without the linker) is the pentasaccharide repeat unit of the O25B major serotype within the extraintestinal pathogenic E. coli (ExPEC) group which expresses a unique O-antigen.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any omega-methyl fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any omega-hydroxy-medium-chain fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-formylglutarate(2-) that has S-configuration.

A synthetic beta-D-glucoside that is a branched decasaccharide derivative consisting of two beta-D-Glc-(1->6)-[alpha-L-Rha-(1->3)]-alpha-D-Glc-(1->3)-alpha-L-Rha2Ac-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc pentasaccharide units linked (1->4) between the GlcNac residue at the reducing end of one unit and the OH at position 4 of the alpha-D-glucose residue of the other unit. An aminoethyl linker from the reducing-end GlcNAc residue allows for efficient conjugation to a carrier protein.

A synthetic beta-D-glucoside that is a branched pentadecasaccharide derivative consisting of three beta-D-Glc-(1->6)-[alpha-L-Rha-(1->3)]-alpha-D-Glc-(1->3)-alpha-L-Rha2Ac-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc pentasaccharide units linked (1->4) between the GlcNac residue at the reducing end of one unit and the OH at position 4 of the alpha-D-glucose residue of the adjacent unit. An aminoethyl linker from the reducing-end GlcNAc residue allows for efficient conjugation to a carrier protein.
